page.title: 07GOYT VALLEY-WOODLAND
page.content: In the relict woodland areas, various types of fungi thrive and foxgloves inhabit the edges. The impenetrable conifers of the newly forested areas shade all ground cover out of existence, but rose-bay willow-herb and brambles occur at the edges. Most woodland mammals are nocturnal, such as the fox, badger, hedgehog and long-tailed field mouse. Insect eating summer visitors, like the redstart, make bird watching in the woodlands an exciting pastime. Resident birds include the jay, magpie (locally named pienet), tree creeper, goldcrest and wren.
